Dockie Applied AI Engineer Take-Home
Overview
Build a production-minded MVP for a shipment-tracking copilot for customers shipping vehicles by sea.
This is an applied AI assignment. We are not looking for a perfect global shipping platform. We are looking for a clear, working product that shows good engineering judgment, solid AI UX, and strong software practices.
You may use AI tools such as Cursor, Copilot, or similar during the exercise. We care about the quality of your decisions, implementation, and explanation.
Timebox
Recommended effort: up to 1 week
You do not need to build everything perfectly
We will evaluate your work relative to the time available and in comparison with other candidates
Compensation
This take-home is paid
You will receive $50 for completing and submitting the task, whether or not your submission is approved or you move forward in the process
Product Scenario
Your user has one or more vehicles being shipped on ro-ro vessels from the US to West Africa.
They want to:
see all of their active shipments
select a shipment and ask questions by text or voice
understand where the shipment is now
understand what vessel it is on
understand latest position, speed, course, ETA, and recent changes
see a map rendered in the chat experience
hear a spoken response from the assistant
The system should answer grounded questions such as:
"Where is my shipment right now?"
"What vessel is it on?"
"How fast is it moving?"
"When will it arrive in Lagos?"
"What changed since yesterday?"
"How reliable is this answer?"
Core Deliverable
Build a shipment-tracking copilot with:
a clean, working frontend
a backend with real application structure
an agent that uses tools or structured retrieval
support for multiple shipments
map rendering inside the chat experience
voice input and spoken output
clear explanation of how the system was built
Required Stack
The following stack choices are compulsory for this take-home:
Python backend
FastAPI
Postgres
Google ADK
AG-UI
You may add other libraries or supporting services if needed, but the core implementation must use the stack above.
Frontend Requirements
The frontend should be polished enough to feel like a real product, not a prototype thrown together at the last minute.
Required:
shipment list or overview screen
ability to open and switch between multiple shipments
chat interface for text interaction
voice input
spoken response output
map card or rich tracking card rendered inside chat
structured shipment details shown alongside the conversation
Design direction:
We will provide a few UI reference screenshots as inspiration
You do not need to match them exactly
We care more about clarity, polish, and interaction quality than visual mimicry
Agent And AI Requirements
Required:
use Google ADK for the agent layer
use AG-UI for the agent-driven UI experience
The agent should:
answer with grounded data, not free-form guessing
use tools, APIs, or structured retrieval where appropriate
render rich UI state in chat when useful
surface evidence, freshness, or confidence where relevant
handle follow-up questions across the same session
Strong plus:
explicit handling of prompt injection or malicious retrieved content
safe tool-calling boundaries
visible explanation of why an answer may be stale or uncertain
Backend Requirements
Build a real backend, not just a mocked frontend.
Required:
Python backend using FastAPI
relational database using Postgres
clear application structure with separation of concerns
HTTP API for the app
at least one CLI workflow for refresh, ingest, or diagnostics
containerized local setup with docker compose
migrations
basic automated tests for meaningful logic
Recommended architecture:
domain logic
application orchestration
infrastructure adapters
external interfaces
Data Requirements
Your system should ingest at least 2 source types, for example:
shipment or order data
vessel position data
schedule or route-intent data
Required:
persist raw upstream payloads before normalization
normalize into canonical records such as shipment, vessel, position, voyage, event, and evidence
support freshness tracking and degraded or stale states
make source provenance visible in either the UI, API, or logs
You may use a mix of:
provided fixtures
one or more live integrations
your own simulated refresh workflows
You will not be penalized for using fixtures if your system design is strong and the product works well.
Security And Reliability Expectations
We will score heavily for software quality, not just demo quality.
Please demonstrate thoughtfulness around:
prompt injection and unsafe retrieved content
secrets and environment configuration
source freshness and stale-data handling
graceful degradation when a source fails
provenance and evidence visibility
sensible logging and traceability
If a source is stale, fragile, or partially trusted, the system should say so instead of acting overly certain.
