Challenge Source Policy Guide
This guide defines how a candidate system should classify and handle upstream sources without depending on any one implementation.
Why This Exists
Maritime OSINT sources are not interchangeable. A source may be publicly visible but still be fragile, license-limited, or unsuitable as a hidden production dependency.
Every source should therefore carry explicit policy metadata.
Required Classification Fields
Each source should be described with these fields:
name
source_class
automation_safety
business_safe_default
role
health_expectation
fallback_behavior
Source Classes
open_data
Use for sources with clear reuse terms and low operational ambiguity.
Typical handling:
eligible for product use by default
safe for repeatable automated ingest
still requires provenance capture and freshness monitoring
public_api_terms
Use for sources that are technically reachable and automatable, but governed by publisher terms, quotas, or fragility concerns.
Typical handling:
allowed for product use with caution
must be rate-limited and monitored
must degrade gracefully when unavailable
noncommercial_or_license_limited
Use for sources that are useful for research but not suitable as the default business-safe production path.
Typical handling:
optional enrichment only
do not make them mandatory for core product workflows
surface licensing caveats clearly
analyst_reference_only
Use for sources that should remain human-in-the-loop unless separately validated.
Typical handling:
support analyst workflows
avoid silent machine dependency
require explicit manual review or later policy promotion
Automation Safety Levels
Use one of these labels:
high: stable enough for normal automation
moderate: usable but needs cautious retry and health monitoring
fragile_scraper: parser drift likely; failures should not be silent
validation_required: do not trust for unattended automation yet
human_in_loop: keep as analyst-facing reference only
Operational Rules
Persist raw payloads before normalization.
Record capture time, source identity, and fetch method.
Never let stale data silently overwrite fresher trusted state.
A parser failure should degrade source health, not disappear.
A licensing-sensitive source should not become a hidden production requirement.
UI and API layers should expose evidence provenance and freshness.
Example Source Policies
AISstream
source_class: public_api_terms
automation_safety: moderate
business_safe_default: yes, with caution
role: live movement bootstrap
health_expectation: best-effort, occasionally degraded
fallback_behavior: keep last known position and lower freshness confidence
Carrier Schedule Pages
source_class: public_api_terms
automation_safety: fragile_scraper
business_safe_default: yes, if monitored
role: route intent and service context
health_expectation: parser break risk
fallback_behavior: retain last trusted schedule snapshot and mark route claims stale
Lagos Port Corroboration Pages
source_class: analyst_reference_only initially
automation_safety: validation_required
business_safe_default: manual_first
role: arrival and berth corroboration
health_expectation: useful but structurally fragile
fallback_behavior: require analyst confirmation until reliability is proven
Official Sanctions Lists
source_class: open_data or public_api_terms
automation_safety: high
business_safe_default: yes
role: compliance and watchlist enrichment
health_expectation: scheduled official updates
fallback_behavior: show last refresh date and coverage gap clearly
Review Questions For Candidates
Can the system explain why a source is or is not trusted for automation?
Can it degrade gracefully when a source is stale, malformed, or unavailable?
Can it keep licensing and product-safety concerns separate from technical reachability?

